(326, 'Background Sources', 'Encyclopedias are generally most useful for&nbsp;<strong>two</strong> things:\n<ul>\n	<li>To introduce a topic, give a brief overview or a definition.</li>\n	<li>To recommend further reading, usually either sound introductions or seminal works.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n{{dab},{1109}, {A to Z of Social Research, 2003.},{01}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1078}, {Blackwell Encyclopedia of Sociology, 2007.},{00}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1177}, {Cambridge Dictionary of Sociology},{01}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{51}, {Credo Reference},{01}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1136}, {Culture Wars: An Encyclopedia of Issues, Viewpoints, and Voices, 2010.},{00}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1275}, {Encyclopedia of Sociology, 2000.},{00}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1080}, {International Encyclopedia of the Social Sciences, 2008.},{01}}<br />\n{{dab},{1081}, {Key Concepts in Critical Social Theory, 2005.},{01}}<br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(327, 'Core Databases', '<span style="font-size: 13px;">Although Summon is often a good starting point, for more focused results, check one of the following, which provide access to materials in sociology:</span><br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{53}, {SOCIndex},{00}} &nbsp;<br />\nA core database, which indexes journals, books, dissertations and conference papers.&nbsp; Use the &quot;Subject Terms&quot; tab at the top of the screen to determine what a particular concept is called and to discover related terms - for instance, checking &quot;poverty&quot; leads to &quot;homelessness,&quot; &quot;downward mobility&quot; and &quot;poor&quot; as additional terms that might be appropriate.&nbsp; You can often start with a keyword search, and then look at relevant entries to see what subject terms or descriptors have been assigned to your topic.<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{153}, {Sociological Abstracts},{00}} &nbsp;<br />\n<span style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Although there is considerable overlap between this database and SocINDEX, SA also has some unique items, and a useful thesaurus of indexing terms:&nbsp; &quot;poverty&quot; leads here to &quot;low income groups&quot; and &quot;underclass&quot;.</span><br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(328, 'Find Full Text', '<span style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">If full text is not immediately accessible via a pdf or html, click on&nbsp;</span><img class="confluence-embedded-image confluence-content-image-border" data-image-="" src="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/download/attachments/23304372/AL_button.gif?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1316396336033&amp;api=v2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 1px solid black; cursor: pointer; max-width: 100%; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;" /><span style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">.&nbsp;<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/AL.jpg" style="width: 521px; height: 278px;" /><br />\n<br />\nIf the article is not available at Drew, click on Interlibrary Loan to request it:</span><br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/ILL-2.jpg" style="width: 491px; height: 364px;" /><br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(330, 'Using ASA Formatting', 'There is a useful guide to American Sociological Association format on Purdue University&#39;s <a href="https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/583/01/">OWL</a>. &nbsp;The complete&nbsp;<em>Style Guide</em> is at the Research Help Desk HM.A547 2010.<br />\n<br />\nASA formatting is one of the options offered by EndNote Web, which will automatically set up your bibliography in a designated style. &nbsp;For a complete guide to setting up and using EndNote Web, check <a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Endnote+Web+Bibliographic+Software">here</a>, or search&nbsp;<em>endnote web</em> on the Drew website.&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(331, 'Search tips', '<ul style="margin: 10px 0px 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">\n	<li>to search as a phrase, use &quot;&quot;. For example &quot;civil rights&quot;</li>\n	<li>to connect synonyms, us OR. For example: &quot;civil rights&quot; OR integration OR segregation</li>\n	<li>truncate endings of words with an *. For example: &quot;civil rights&quot; OR integrat* OR segregat*</li>\n	<li>If you only have a single search box and want to do a complicated search string, use (). (&quot;civil rights&quot; OR integrat* OR segregat*) AND (sport* OR athlet*). This is called nesting by librarians.</li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
