(491, 'Choosing Terms and Combining Them', 'Especially when using a &#39;full text&#39; or &#39;natural language&#39; search, it&#39;s important to think about what terms to use.<br />\n<br />\nWhat different concepts are you interested in combining? One set of terms will define the type of behavior you&#39;re concerned about, the other the setting in which you&#39;re discussing it. So, for instance:<br />\nhomophobia in online gaming\n<ol>\n	<li>Concept 1: academic success</li>\n	<li>Concept 2: character traits</li>\n</ol>\n<br />\nYou also may want to consider different terms which may provide ways to get at the same concept, even if they are not synonyms For instance:\n<ol>\n	<li>academic success, educational success, educational achievement</li>\n	<li>personality traits, character traits, personality&nbsp;characteristics</li>\n	<li>higher education, college, university</li>\n</ol>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(492, 'Get full text', '<strong>Full text available&nbsp;</strong><br />\n<br />\nClick directly to the full text if available in a database, or click on &nbsp; <img src="http://depts.drew.edu/lib/AL_button.gif" />&nbsp; &nbsp;to find the full text in another database.The&nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/Library/Drew+ArticleLinker" target="_blank">Article Linker guide</a>&nbsp;provides additional instructions for finding full text, either online or in print/microfilm format within the library.<br />\n<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/holdings.gif" style="width: 553px; height: 508px;" /><br />\n<br />\n<strong>Full text not available</strong><br />\n<br />\nDon&#39;t give up! &nbsp;There are other ways to get the information you are seeking.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nIf the library does not have the item, use the Interlibrary Loan Request to request a copy of it; we&#39;ll get it from another library and post it to you online.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(493, 'Searching SUMMON', '{{dab},{2}, {SUMMON},{00}}&nbsp;is a &#39;natural language&#39; search, which interprets your search terms in a way similar to Google&#39;s search function, and which includes information on as many as possible of all the resources the library has, from government documents to specific journal articles.<br />\n<br />\nNatural language searching may require you to try several different combinations of terms to get the best results to appear near the top. Though you can search on <b>combating sexisum in online gaming</b>, if you search on&nbsp;<strong>sexism &quot;online gaming&quot;</strong> you get a different set of results. &nbsp;Once you have a set of results, typically a large one, you limit it down using the options on the left, just as you would when viewing an online shopping site:<br />\n&nbsp;<img alt="Summon Search Process" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/summonsearch.png" style="width: 446px; height: 289px;" /><br />\n<br />\nSpecial tools for Summon:\n<ul>\n	<li>&quot;phrase search&quot; -- put a phrase inside of quotation marks</li>\n	<li>+required term -- put a + plus sign in front of a term that HAS to be in the results</li>\n	<li>AND and OR: use AND in all caps to combine two separate concepts; use OR in all caps to combine alternative concepts:&nbsp;</li>\n	<li><strong>social media AND privacy</strong>&nbsp;</li>\n	<li><strong>college OR university</strong></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(494, 'Evaluating sources', '<strong>SCHOLARLY VS. POPULAR</strong>\n<p>Scholarly articles</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Identifying scholarly articles. &nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/Library/Identifying+Scholarly+Journals" rel="nofollow" style="color: rgb(50, 108, 166); text-decoration: none;">CLICK HERE</a>&nbsp;for more information from Drew&#39;s Library website.</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{1120}, {Strategies for reading journal articles. },{01}}</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{1118}, {Strategies for reading journal articles - checklist},{01}}</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Popular articles from respected sources</h4>\n\n<ul >\n	<li>Click on the title below for an excellent comparison of scholarly magazines vs. popular magazines vs. trade magazines/journals from NC State University.&nbsp;<br />\n	<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><a class="external-link" href="http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/guides/spmaterials" rel="nofollow" style="color: rgb(50, 108, 166); text-decoration: none;">&ldquo;Scholarly vs. Popular Materials Research Guide&rdquo;</a>. &nbsp;NCSU Libraries. NC State University. n.d. Web. 4 March 2014.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">​<br />\n<strong>EVALUATING A SOURCE:</strong></span><br />\n<br />\n<em>ACCURACY/VALIDITY&nbsp;</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Is the article well researched and information properly cited?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Are facts and statistics documented?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Is there a bibliography or list of resources? (pro tip: not all articles with bibliographies are scholarly, but all scholarly articles have bibliographies!)</li>\n	<li>Do the facts presented match those in similar sources?</li>\n</ul>\n<em>AUTHORITY</em>&nbsp;\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Who is the author or authoring organization?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Is contact information provided?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>What are the qualifications or credentials of the author?</li>\n	<li>Does the author have expertise in the topic covered?</li>\n	<li>What is his or her&nbsp;institutional affiliation?&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<em>OBJECTIVITY&nbsp;</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Are the goals/aims of the authors clearly stated?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Are there biases in the document?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Does the author address opposing views or facts?</li>\n</ul>\n<em>CURRENCY/TIMEFRAME</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Is this up-to-date (if you need up-to-date information)</li>\n	<li>Is this from the right time period if you need a primary source?&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<em>PUBLISHING BODY/SOURCE&nbsp;</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Who &quot;publishes&quot; or sponsors the journal or other publication?</li>\n	<li>Is there a connection to a larger sponsoring organization?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>What is the subject expertise/possible bias of the publisher or organization?</li>\n</ul>\n<em>RELEVANCY/COVERAGE</em>&nbsp;\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Is the information presented relevant to your topic?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style="margin: 10px 0px 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">More excellent information about evaluating resources</p>\n\n<ul style="margin: 10px 0px 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">\n	<li><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&ldquo;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Critical Evaluation of Resources.&rdquo;&nbsp;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">University of California Berkeley Library. &nbsp;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">University of California. 2009. 4 March 2014.</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&nbsp;<a class="external-link" href="http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/instruct/guides/evaluation.html" rel="nofollow" style="color: rgb(50, 108, 166); text-decoration: none;">http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/instruct/guides/evaluation.html</a></span></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(495, 'Get full text', '<strong>Full text available&nbsp;</strong><br />\n<br />\nClick directly to the full text if available in a database, or click on &nbsp; <img src="http://depts.drew.edu/lib/AL_button.gif" />&nbsp; &nbsp;to find the full text in another database.The&nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/Library/Drew+ArticleLinker" target="_blank">Article Linker guide</a>&nbsp;provides additional instructions for finding full text, either online or in print/microfilm format within the library.<br />\n<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/holdings.gif" style="width: 553px; height: 508px;" /><br />\n<br />\n<strong>Full text not available?</strong><br />\n<br />\nDon&#39;t give up! &nbsp;There are other ways to get the information you are seeking.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nIf the library does not have the item, use the<strong> Interlibrary Loan Request (a.k.a. ILLiad)&nbsp;</strong>to request a copy of it; we&#39;ll get it from another library and post it to you online.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(496, 'Citing Your Sources', '<ul>\n	<li><span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">Look for &quot;<strong>Cite</strong>&quot; links in all your databases.&nbsp;</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">Be certain to use the format recommended by your professor.</span></li>\n	<li><em>An excellent resource about MLA formatting from Purdue OWL Lab:<br />\n	&nbsp;<a href="http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/747/01/"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Angeli, E., Brizee, A., Keck, R., Paiz, J., Russell, T. &quot;</span><span style="color: rgb(96, 60, 20);">MLA Formatting and Style Guide</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">.&quot;&nbsp;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The Purdue OWL</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">. Purdue U Writing Lab, 2012. Web. 4 March&nbsp;2014.</span></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/747/01/">http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/747/01/</a></em></li>\n	<li><strong><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Endnote+Web+Bibliographic+Software" style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">EndnoteWeb</a></strong><span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">&nbsp;will help you format your references (either parenthetical or endnotes), keep track of your articles, and set up your bibliography/reference list. &nbsp;Ask about it at the Research Helpdesk!</span></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(498, 'Get full text', '<strong>Full text available&nbsp;</strong><br />\n<br />\nClick directly to the full text if available in a database, or click on &nbsp; <img src="http://depts.drew.edu/lib/AL_button.gif" />&nbsp; &nbsp;to find the full text in another database.The&nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/Library/Drew+ArticleLinker" target="_blank">Article Linker guide</a>&nbsp;provides additional instructions for finding full text, either online or in print/microfilm format within the library.<br />\n<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/holdings.gif" style="width: 553px; height: 508px;" /><br />\n<br />\nSometimes something will come in Summon as online, only to say Drew Print Serials. You&#39;ll find current issues of print journals in the Atrium on Level C of the Library, and back issues downstairs on Level A in the moving shelves.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Full text not available</strong><br />\n<br />\nDon&#39;t give up! &nbsp;There are other ways to get the information you are seeking.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nIf the library does not have the item, use the Interlibrary Loan Request to request a copy of it; we&#39;ll get it from another library and post it to you online.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(499, 'Subject Resources', '<strong>GENERAL</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>{{dab},{2}, {SUMMON},{00}}</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{4}, {Academic Search Premier},{00}}</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<strong>ART</strong>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>{{dab},{138}, {Oxford Art Online},{01}} -- Background material</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{962}, {International Bibliography of Art},{01}}&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">&nbsp;-- Articles</span></li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<strong>MUSIC</strong>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>{{dab},{179}, {Oxford Music Online},{01}} -- Background material</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{180}, {RILM Abstracts of Music Literature},{01}} -- Articles</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{98}, {International Index to the Performing Arts},{01}} -- Articles</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<strong>FILM</strong>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>{{dab},{98}, {International Index to the Performing Arts},{01}} -- Articles</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{97}, {Film Index International},{01}}</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{96}, {FIAF},{01}}</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{40}, {MLA Bibliography},{01}}</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<strong>LITERATURE</strong>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>{{dab},{3}, {Literature Resource Center},{00}}</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{40}, {MLA Bibliography},{01}}</li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(501, 'Bibliography Help', '<ul>\n	<li>{{dab},{916}, {MLA Handbook for Writers of Research Papers},{00}}</li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.6em;">An excellent resource about MLA formatting from Purdue OWL Lab: <a href="http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/747/01/">http://</a></span><a href="http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/747/01/">owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/747/01/</a></li>\n	<li>EndnoteWeb is a citation manager available for free to Drewids,&nbsp;with a Microsoft Word Add-in that helps you format your bibliography &amp; notes.<br />\n	Instructions here:&nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/x/JwHy">https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/x/JwHy</a></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(502, 'Searching SUMMON', '{{dab},{2}, {SUMMON},{00}}&nbsp;is a &#39;natural language&#39; search, which interprets your search terms in a way similar to Google&#39;s search function, and which includes information on as many as possible of all the resources the library has, from government documents to specific journal articles.<br />\n<br />\nNatural language searching may require you to try several different combinations of terms to get the best results to appear near the top. Though you can search on <b>combating sexisum in online gaming</b>, if you search on&nbsp;<strong>sexism &quot;online gaming&quot;</strong> you get a different set of results. &nbsp;Once you have a set of results, typically a large one, you limit it down using the options on the left, just as you would when viewing an online shopping site:<br />\n&nbsp;<img alt="Summon Search Process" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/summonsearch.png" style="width: 446px; height: 289px;" /><br />\n<br />\nSpecial tools for Summon:\n<ul>\n	<li>&quot;phrase search&quot; -- put a phrase inside of quotation marks</li>\n	<li>+required term -- put a + plus sign in front of a term that HAS to be in the results</li>\n	<li>AND and OR: use AND in all caps to combine two separate concepts; use OR in all caps to combine alternative concepts:&nbsp;</li>\n	<li><strong>street art AND london</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>film OR movie</strong></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
