(624, 'Evaluating resources', '<strong>Scholarly articles vs. popular articles</strong>: Good discussion about each article type&nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/Library/Identifying+Scholarly+Journals">HERE</a> in Drew Library resources.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Popular articles from respected sources:</strong> Identifying a source that is reliable but not necessarily scholarly. Good discussion <a href="http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/tutorials/scholarly-popular/">HERE</a> from NCState Library. &nbsp;<br />\n<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;"><strong>&quot;Critical evaluation of resources&quot; </strong>:&nbsp;</span>From Cal - Berkeley Library &nbsp;<a href="http://guides.lib.berkeley.edu/evaluating-resources">HERE&nbsp;</a><br />\n<br />\nArticle Examples:<br />\n{{fil},{_mashmun/scholarly1.pdf}, {Example 1}}<br />\n{{fil},{_mashmun/scholarly2.pdf}, {Example 2}}<br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(628, 'Basic Resources', '{{dab},{2}, {SUMMON},{00}}&nbsp;<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">A &#39;natural language&#39; search that works similarly to Google/Google Scholar, combining all the words you put in and approximating how they should appear in the text of results.<br />\nExamples:&nbsp;<br />\n<em>low fat vs. low carbohydrate diets</em><br />\nBEST FEATURE: &quot;Facets&quot; in left column allow you to limit your results<br />\nAdditional features: finds books, government documents and websites as well as journal articles.<br />\nWatch out for:<br />\n- Limiting to Peer Reviewed Articles<br />\n- Email yourself the Bibliography Citations for your results in the format you choose</span><br />\n- use quotation marks around phrases, for example &quot;fat acceptance&quot;<br />\n<br />\n<strong>{{dab},{4}, {Academic Search Premier},{00}}</strong><br />\nA library type search that uses subject headings describing the contents and AND / OR connectors to pinpoint appropriate results<br />\nExample:<br />\n<img alt="Low-carb" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/ac-diet.png" style="width: 532px; height: 140px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;" /><br />\n<br />\nWatch out for:<br />\n- Limiting to &quot;Scholarly (Peer Reviewed) Journals<br />\n- Use &quot;Search for Article&quot; button to find out if the article is online', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(629, 'Finding Background', '{{dab},{51}, {Credo Reference},{01}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{689}, {ProCon.org: Pros and Cons of Controversial Issues},{01}}', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(631, 'Choosing Terms and Combining Them', 'Especially when using a &#39;full text&#39; or &#39;natural language&#39; search, it&#39;s important to think about what terms to use.<br />\n<br />\nWhat different concepts are you interested in combining?<br />\nAre the concepts pretty much interchangeable, or do you need both of them?<br />\n<br />\nSo, for instance:<br />\nlow-carb vs. low-fat diets\n<ol>\n	<li>Concept 1: low carbohydrate diets</li>\n	<li>Concept 2: low fat diets</li>\n</ol>\nYou need <strong>both </strong>in each article. Combine with AND:<br />\nLow-fat diets AND low carbohydrate diets<br />\n<br />\nhowever, dieting and weight loss are pretty interchangeable, so you can combine them with OR:<br />\ndieting OR weight loss<br />\n<br />\nYou also may want to consider different terms which may provide ways to get at the same concept, even if they are not synonyms, and use OR to combine them. For instance:\n<ol>\n	<li>online gaming, computer gaming, gamers,&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">World of Warcraft, Xbox Live</span></li>\n	<li>sports, athletics, games</li>\n	<li>classroom, schools, high school, elementary school, classes, education</li>\n	<li>racism, white privilege, prejudice&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(632, 'Evaluating Sources', 'Go to this page:<br />\n<b style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8000001907349px; line-height: normal;"><a href="http://tinyurl.com/WRTG115-Myers-Library">http://tinyurl.com/WRTG115-Myers-Library</a></b><br />\n<br />\nand brainstorm clues for evaluating sources.<br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(633, 'Evaluating sources', '<strong>SCHOLARLY VS. POPULAR</strong>\n<p>Scholarly articles</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Identifying scholarly articles. &nbsp;<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/Library/Identifying+Scholarly+Journals" rel="nofollow" style="color: rgb(50, 108, 166); text-decoration: none;">CLICK HERE</a>&nbsp;for more information from Drew&#39;s Library website.</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{1120}, {Strategies for reading journal articles. },{01}}</li>\n	<li>{{dab},{1118}, {Strategies for reading journal articles - checklist},{01}}</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Popular articles from respected sources</h4>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Click on the title below for an excellent comparison of scholarly magazines vs. popular magazines vs. trade magazines/journals from NC State University.&nbsp;<br />\n	<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><a class="external-link" href="http://www.lib.ncsu.edu/guides/spmaterials" rel="nofollow" style="color: rgb(50, 108, 166); text-decoration: none;">&ldquo;Scholarly vs. Popular Materials Research Guide&rdquo;</a>. &nbsp;NCSU Libraries. NC State University. n.d. Web. 4 March 2014.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">​<br />\n<strong>EVALUATING A SOURCE:</strong></span><br />\n<br />\n<em>ACCURACY/VALIDITY&nbsp;</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Is the article well researched and information properly cited?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Are facts and statistics documented?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Is there a bibliography or list of resources? (pro tip: not all articles with bibliographies are scholarly, but all scholarly articles have bibliographies!)</li>\n	<li>Do the facts presented match those in similar sources?</li>\n</ul>\n<em>AUTHORITY</em>&nbsp;\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Who is the author or authoring organization?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Is contact information provided?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>What are the qualifications or credentials of the author?</li>\n	<li>Does the author have expertise in the topic covered?</li>\n	<li>What is his or her&nbsp;institutional affiliation?&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<em>OBJECTIVITY&nbsp;</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Are the goals/aims of the authors clearly stated?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Are there biases in the document?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>Does the author address opposing views or facts?</li>\n</ul>\n<em>CURRENCY/TIMEFRAME</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Is this up-to-date (if you need up-to-date information)</li>\n	<li>Is this from the right time period if you need a primary source?&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<em>PUBLISHING BODY/SOURCE&nbsp;</em>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Who &quot;publishes&quot; or sponsors the journal or other publication?</li>\n	<li>Is there a connection to a larger sponsoring organization?&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>What is the subject expertise/possible bias of the publisher or organization?</li>\n</ul>\n<em>RELEVANCY/COVERAGE</em>&nbsp;\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Is the information presented relevant to your topic?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style="margin: 10px 0px 0px; padding: 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">More excellent information about evaluating resources</p>\n\n<ul style="margin: 10px 0px 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">\n	<li><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&ldquo;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Critical Evaluation of Resources.&rdquo;&nbsp;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">University of California Berkeley Library. &nbsp;</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">University of California. 2009. 4 March 2014.</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&nbsp;<a class="external-link" href="http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/instruct/guides/evaluation.html" rel="nofollow" style="color: rgb(50, 108, 166); text-decoration: none;">http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/instruct/guides/evaluation.html</a></span></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
