(645, 'Basic Resources', '{{dab},{2}, {SUMMON},{00}}&nbsp;<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">A &#39;natural language&#39; search that works similarly to Google/Google Scholar, combining all the words you put in and approximating how they should appear in the text of results.<br />\nExamples:&nbsp;<br />\n<em>cultural differences in comedy</em><br />\nBEST FEATURE: &quot;Facets&quot; in left column allow you to limit your results, by subject, type, date, etc.<br />\nAdditional features: finds books, government documents and websites as well as journal articles.<br />\nWatch out for:<br />\n- Limiting to Peer Reviewed Articles<br />\n- Email yourself the Bibliography Citations for your results in the format you choose</span><br />\n- use quotation marks around phrases, for example &quot;mass media&quot; or &quot;vaccine injury&quot;<br />\n<br />\n<strong>{{dab},{4}, {Academic Search Premier},{00}}</strong><br />\nA library type search that uses subject headings describing the contents and AND / OR connectors to pinpoint appropriate results<br />\nExample:<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jheise/example1.png" style="width: 522px; height: 120px;" /><br />\n<br />\nWatch out for:<br />\n- Limiting to &quot;Scholarly (Peer Reviewed) Journals<br />\n- Use &quot;Search for Article&quot; button to find out if the article is online<br />\n- truncation: using racis* for racist, racisim; vaccin* for vaccination, vaccines, etc.<br />\n- quote phrases, &quot;west africa&quot;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(646, 'Choosing Terms and Combining Them', 'Especially when using a &#39;full text&#39; or &#39;natural language&#39; search, it&#39;s important to think about what terms to use.<br />\n<br />\nWhat different concepts are you interested in combining?<br />\nAre the concepts pretty much interchangeable, or do you need both of them?<br />\n<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">Especially when using a &#39;full text&#39; or &#39;natural language&#39; search, it&#39;s important to think about what terms to use.</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">Remember: phrases &quot;in quotes&quot; and truncat*</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">Natural Language search engines first try to find/display items with all your terms in them, then move to displaying items with only some of your terms in them. You can force a term to be included by using + before it:</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">+&quot;anne sexton&quot; witch fairy</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<br />\n<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">In&nbsp;Databases such as Academic Search Premiere you&#39;ll need to use special connnection words for different concepts:&nbsp;<strong>AND</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>OR</strong></span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">What different concepts are you interested in combining?</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">Are the concepts pretty much interchangeable, or do you need both of them?</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">madness in Anne Sexton&#39;s work</span>\n<ol style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">\n	<li>Concept 1: madness</li>\n	<li>Concept 2: Anne Sexton</li>\n</ol>\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">You need&nbsp;</span><strong style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">both&nbsp;</strong><span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">in each article. Combine with AND:</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;">&quot;anne sexton&quot; AND madness</span><br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\n<br style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;" />\nHowever, we use the term &quot;mental illness&quot; while she used the term &quot;madness.&quot; Either one will work, so they function as synonyms and you combine them with OR:<br />\nmadness OR mental illness<br />\n<br />\nYou also may want to consider different terms which may provide ways to get at the same concept, even if they are not synonyms, and use OR to combine them. For instance:\n<ol>\n	<li>gender, women (or men), sex, femin* (or masculin*), female (or male)</li>\n	<li>death, dying, decay</li>\n	<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">metaphor, allusion, language</span></li>\n	<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">psychology, psychiatry, mental illness</span></li>\n	<li><span style="line-height: 1.6em;">symbols, images, metaphors</span></li>\n</ol>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL);
