(755, 'Endnote Resources', '<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/x/JwHy">How to use Endnote Basic/Endnote Web</a><br />\n&nbsp;\n<ul style="margin: 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px; background-color: rgb(255, 253, 246);">\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Endnote+Web+-+Signing+up+for+an+Account" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Endnote Web - Signing up for an Account</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Entering+Your+Own+Citations+in+EndnoteWeb" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Entering Your Own Citations in EndnoteWeb</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Sharing+your+Endnote+References+with+your+instructor" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Sharing your Endnote References with your instructor</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Emailing+References+from+Endnote+Basic" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Emailing References from Endnote Basic</a></li>\n</ul>\n', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(756, 'Drew''s New York Times Subscription', 'Your instructor may ask you to read specific articles in the online New York times.<br />\nYou can sign up for free online access to the New York Times through Drew Library&#39;s subscription:<br />\n<a href="http://nytimes.com/pass">http://nytimes.com/pass</a> using your Drew email address.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(757, 'Wall Street Journal', 'The {{dab},{1253}, {Wall Street Journal},{00}} can be found online, also. Use the &quot;Search Inside this Publication&quot; option to pull up the articles you&#39;re interested in.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(758, 'Endnote Resources', '<a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/x/JwHy">How to use Endnote Basic/Endnote Web</a><br />\n&nbsp;\n<ul style="margin: 0px; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px; background-color: rgb(255, 253, 246);">\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Endnote+Web+-+Signing+up+for+an+Account" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Endnote Web - Signing up for an Account</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Entering+Your+Own+Citations+in+EndnoteWeb" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Entering Your Own Citations in EndnoteWeb</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/x/KQHy">Capturing References in Endnote Web</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Sharing+your+Endnote+References+with+your+instructor" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Sharing your Endnote References with your instructor</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Emailing+References+from+Endnote+Basic" style="color: rgb(59, 115, 175); text-decoration: none;">Emailing References from Endnote Basic</a></li>\n	<li>A <a href="https://youtu.be/8Lmt8AUN6S4"><strong>video of using Cite While You Write</strong></a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/x/MwHy">Using Cite While You Write</a></li>\n</ul>\nNote: Students at the Technology Help Desk are trained to help you install Cite While You Write.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(760, 'Drew''s New York Times Subscription', 'Your instructor may ask you to read specific articles in the online New York times.<br />\nYou can sign up for free online access to the New York Times through Drew Library&#39;s subscription:<br />\n<a href="http://nytimes.com/pass">http://nytimes.com/pass</a> using your Drew email address.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(761, 'General Information Search Engines', 'Everyone&#39;s encountered bad information, like bad fish or other products, once in a while. But you can protect yourself by looking for information in more reputable sources (just like shopping at the most reputable retailers!).<br />\nHere are some resources for finding information available to you through Drew&#39;s library:\n<h4>{{dab},{2}, {SUMMON},{00}}</h4>\nThe library tries to provide access to the best books, journal articles, newspapers and other sources. SUMMON is a took for searching across almost all those resources, Google-style. You can exclude newspaper articles or restrict just to scholarly journal articles or books. Selecting descriptions of sources and emailing them to yourself also gives you the option to get a citation* for each one to put in your bibliography. It&#39;s on the top of the Research Resources page.<br />\n<br />\n&lt;h2&gt;{{dab},{4}, {Academic Search Premier},{00}}&lt;/h2&gt;<br />\nAcademic Search Premier is a database that lets you look for information in a subset of journals and newspapers, including some that Drew doesn&#39;t own directly-- to get full text of those, you can use Interlibrary Loan. It doesn&#39;t use Google-type searching; you&#39;ll need to connect terms with AND:<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/DSem-ASP.png" style="border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; width: 409px; height: 92px;" /><br />\nYuo can restrict your search to scholarly articles, and email yourself the citation.<br />\nLook under List of Resources by Title -&gt; A or List of Resources by Subject -&gt; General to find this one.<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{16}, {Drew Library Catalog},{00}}<br />\nTo find books and other material - DVDs, government documents, etc. - owned by Drew University, search the Library Catalog.<br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(762, 'Finding Articles, Essays and Papers', 'Specialized indexes, such as ProQuest Sociology or SOCIndex, are the best tools for finding scholarly material on a sociological topic because:\n<ul>\n	<li>Most of the material they contain is academic or professional in nature.</li>\n	<li>The vocabulary they use is often more focused, and generally winnows out irrelevant material.</li>\n	<li>The links to full text they provide are usually more robust than those of Google Scholar.</li>\n</ul>\nOne challenge that you may face, though, is in linking a sociological perspective or theory to a specific sociological phenomenon. &nbsp;Unless an article is&nbsp;<strong>primarily</strong> focusing on how a specific theory can be used to understand a problem, most indexes will not mention the theory. &nbsp;To address this, you may want to identify some of the major scholars who are connected with the particular theory you want to use. &nbsp;To do that, check one or two of the encyclopedias listed above - the most useful for this are probably&nbsp;<em>Social Science Jargon-Buster&nbsp;</em>and&nbsp;<em>Blackwell Dictionary of Sociology</em>. &nbsp;Then add those scholars to your search. &nbsp;For instance, if you were planning to use symbolic interactionism, you could find that George Mead, Erving Goffman, Herbert Blumer or Howard Becker might be included as key proponents of the theory.<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{151}, {Proquest Sociology},{01}}, plus indexing of many more.<br />\nThis database is particularly useful for linking theories with phenomena because the full text (where theorists are more likely to be mentioned) is often available. &nbsp;Start by searching full-text (the default) and narrow your search to terms found only in the abstract or indexing, which will focus your results:<br />\n<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/SOC242-proquest.jpg" style="width: 637px; height: 94px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;" /><br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{53}, {SOCIndex},{01}}<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Note:</strong> Both these databases include conference papers (usually labeled). &nbsp;To see if these have been published on the web, search their titles on&nbsp;{{dab},{18}, {Google Scholar},{00}}.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Not full text?</strong><br />\nUse&nbsp;{{dab},{1123}, {InterLibrary Loan},{00}} to request the item from another library.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(763, 'Using ASA Formatting', 'There is a useful guide to American Sociological Association format on Purdue University&#39;s <a href="https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/583/01/" target="_blank">OWL</a>. &nbsp;The complete&nbsp;<em>Style Guide</em> is at the Research Help Desk HM.A547 2010.<br />\n<br />\nASA formatting is one of the options offered by EndNote Web, which will automatically set up your bibliography in a designated style. &nbsp;For a complete guide to setting up and using EndNote Web, check <a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Endnote+Basic+aka+Endnote+Web+Bibliographic+Software" target="_blank">here</a>, or search&nbsp;<em>endnote web</em> on the Drew website.&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(764, 'Finding Books', 'Although the topic of your paper may be narrower than that of a book (in fact, it probably should be!), there may be books that deal with specific theories or problems that may be useful to you. &nbsp;To find them, search the&nbsp;{{dab},{16}, {Drew Library Catalog},{00}}:<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/SOC242Catalog.jpg" style="width: 319px; height: 48px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;" /><br />\n<br />\nIf you are looking for a specific book, search the author and the title:<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/SOC242-exactcat.jpg" style="width: 332px; height: 49px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;" />', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(765, 'Before You Start Your Research. . .', 'What would the perfect source be? &nbsp;Perhaps you&#39;re looking for articles by respected authors that apply the specific theory or perspective that you want to use to the particular phenomenon or problem that you really find fascinating. &nbsp;And it&#39;s possible that &quot;perfect source&quot; actually exists!<br />\n<br />\nOr not.<br />\n<br />\nAnd would it be &quot;perfect&quot; if it did? &nbsp;That would mean you have nothing to add to the scholarly conversation.<br />\n<br />\nYou may need to do research on:\n<ul>\n	<li>How your theory is applied to a broad area (like deviance).</li>\n	<li>AND on the particular problem that you&#39;re investigating</li>\n</ul>\nAnd then YOU put the two together. &nbsp;The examples below assume that there may be scholarship available on specific phenomena, analyzed from a particular theoretical perspective. &nbsp;But that may not be the case! &nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(766, 'Finding Background Information', 'It&#39;s a good idea, before you start serious searching, to have some understanding of the issues and theories that you&#39;re going to explore. &nbsp;This may come from your assigned readings, from class sessions or textbooks. &nbsp;Additional sources may be encyclopedias or dictionaries, which try to give quick overviews, frequently including&nbsp;<strong>recommended</strong> readings or authors, which are often good places to start. &nbsp;Some possibilities include:<br />\n<br />\n<span style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.8000011444092px;">{{dab},{915}, {Blackwell Dictionary of Sociology},{01}}</span><br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1258}, {Social Science Jargon-Buster, 2007},{01}}<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{1078}, {Blackwell Encyclopedia of Sociology, 2007.},{01}}<br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
