(908, 'Core Databases', '<span style="font-size: 13px;">Although Summon is often a good starting point, for more focused results, check one of the following, which provide access to materials in sociology:</span><br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{53}, {SOCIndex},{00}} &nbsp;<br />\nA core database, which indexes journals, books, dissertations and conference papers.&nbsp; Use the &quot;Subject Terms&quot; tab at the top of the screen to determine what a particular concept is called and to discover related terms - for instance, checking &quot;poverty&quot; leads to &quot;homelessness,&quot; &quot;downward mobility&quot; and &quot;poor&quot; as additional terms that might be appropriate.&nbsp; You can often start with a keyword search, and then look at relevant entries to see what subject terms or descriptors have been assigned to your topic.<br />\n<br />\n{{dab},{153}, {Sociological Abstracts},{00}} &nbsp;<br />\n<span style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 20px;">Although there is considerable overlap between this database and SocINDEX, SA also has some unique items, and a useful thesaurus of indexing terms:&nbsp; &quot;poverty&quot; leads here to &quot;low income groups&quot; and &quot;underclass&quot;.</span><br />\n&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(909, 'Using ASA Formatting', 'There is a useful guide to American Sociological Association format on Purdue University&#39;s <a href="https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/583/01/">OWL</a>. &nbsp;The complete&nbsp;<em>Style Guide</em> is at the Research Help Desk HM.A547 2010.<br />\n<br />\nASA formatting is one of the options offered by EndNote Web, which will automatically set up your bibliography in a designated style. &nbsp;For a complete guide to setting up and using EndNote Web, check <a href="https://uknow.drew.edu/confluence/display/techdocs/Endnote+Web+Bibliographic+Software">here</a>, or search&nbsp;<em>endnote web</em> on the Drew website.&nbsp;', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
(910, 'General Social Survey', 'The <a href="http://gss.norc.org/get-documentation">GSS Codebook</a>&nbsp;lists all the variables for which the General Social Survey has had questions and is approximate 3500 pages. &nbsp;<a href="http://gss.norc.org/documents/codebook/GSS_Codebook_AppendixV.pdf">Appendix V</a> arranges the questions by subject (a mere 90 pages). &nbsp;Search for a term (religion in the example below) that interests you:<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/GSS-Subject.png" style="width: 570px; height: 231px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;" /><br />\nThe left column gives the basic subject of a question. The right column is the mnemonic, which you can use to find the exact wording of the item in the <a href="http://gss.norc.org/documents/codebook/GSS_Codebook_mainbody.pdf">Main Body</a> of the Codebook:<br />\n<img alt="" src="http://walter.drew.edu/splus/assets/users/_jcaldwel/GSSQuestion.jpg" style="width: 683px; height: 227px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;" /><br />\nNotice the question was only asked in 2004 and 2014 - the frequency of a question&nbsp;<strong>may</strong> indicate that there will be more research available on it.', NULL, 0, 'Basic', '', 0, 0, NULL),
